In Java, an abstract class is a class that cannot be instantiated on its own and is typically used as a base class for other classes. It serves as a blueprint for other classes by providing common methods and fields that subclasses can inherit and override. 

Here are some key points associated with abstract classes in Java:

1. Abstract Keyword: To declare an abstract class, you use the `abstract` keyword in the class declaration.

2. Abstract Methods: Abstract classes can have abstract methods, which are methods that are declared without a method body. Subclasses that inherit from an abstract class must provide concrete implementations for these abstract methods. Abstract methods are also declared using the `abstract` keyword.

3. Concrete Methods: Abstract classes can also have concrete methods that provide a default implementation. Subclasses can choose to override these methods or use the provided implementation.

   ```java
   abstract class MyAbstractClass {
       abstract void myAbstractMethod();

       void myConcreteMethod() {
           // Default implementation
       }
   }
   ```

4. Inheritance: Subclasses that extend an abstract class must either implement all the abstract methods declared in the abstract class or be declared as abstract themselves. In other words, you cannot have a concrete subclass of an abstract class that does not provide implementations for all abstract methods.

   ```java
   class MyConcreteSubclass extends MyAbstractClass {
       @Override
       void myAbstractMethod() {
           // Provide an implementation
       }
   }
   ```

5. Instantiation: You cannot create an instance of an abstract class.

